WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.500
My name is Elena Chistykova. I am a personal consultant and a business coach.

00:05.000 --> 00:09.500
I am a member of the International Association of Cross-Cultural Management of Vienna, Austria.

00:10.000 --> 00:14.000
I work with well-known training companies and training centers.

00:14.500 --> 00:19.500
Today I will tell you about the laws of effective business relations.

00:20.000 --> 00:24.500
You will be able to better understand yourself, establish effective interaction in the team,

00:25.000 --> 00:28.500
and you will be able to successfully cope with complex communication tasks.

00:29.500 --> 00:31.000
Business communication.

00:31.500 --> 00:38.000
By business communication we mean any communication that is aimed at obtaining a specific business result.

00:38.500 --> 00:45.000
This can be public speeches, presentations, negotiations or meetings.

00:45.500 --> 00:49.000
It can be telephone communication with suppliers and customers.

00:49.500 --> 00:55.000
It can be business interactions that take place at workplaces.

00:56.000 --> 00:59.500
What is the essence of business communication and what makes it different from personal communication?

01:00.000 --> 01:10.500
The fact is that the definition of business relations says that business communication is aimed at obtaining a specific business result.

01:11.000 --> 01:16.500
Therefore, in the two main components of communication, informational and emotional,

01:17.000 --> 01:20.500
the main attention is paid to the informational.

01:21.500 --> 01:26.000
In business communication we always talk more about business, about something specific.

01:26.500 --> 01:33.000
In personal communication, the goal of personal communication is communication itself, our relationship.

01:33.500 --> 01:38.000
Most of the time we communicate at the emotional level.

01:38.500 --> 01:42.000
A person feels comfortable when communication takes place at both levels.

01:42.500 --> 01:48.000
Therefore, if we communicate only at the informational level, if we communicate dryly, without emotions,

01:48.000 --> 01:53.500
it leads to burnout, the motivation of the staff decreases.

01:54.000 --> 01:57.500
No one likes to communicate only about specific results.

01:58.000 --> 02:04.500
Therefore, the question of ethics of business relations, the right regulation,

02:05.000 --> 02:10.500
the right compromise between the result and the relations.

02:11.000 --> 02:15.500
What to do? How to achieve this?

02:15.500 --> 02:19.000
Secrets in effective techniques.

02:19.500 --> 02:29.000
Therefore, today we will talk about the system tasks, the approach to business communication.

02:29.500 --> 02:33.000
Therefore, today we will use a system approach.

02:33.500 --> 02:37.000
We will talk about communication as a whole, about the laws of success,

02:37.500 --> 02:41.000
about the points of vulnerability that can interfere with our effective communication.

02:41.000 --> 02:46.500
We will talk about specific practical skills that will allow us to succeed

02:47.000 --> 02:51.500
in complex business communications and public speeches.

02:52.000 --> 02:59.500
If we approach business communication as a whole, we must consider the business communication strategy.

03:00.000 --> 03:09.500
That is, how we build the goals of business communication and how we go to our specific business result.

03:10.500 --> 03:14.000
There are three main strategies.

03:14.500 --> 03:18.000
The first strategy is the strategy of the conqueror.

03:18.500 --> 03:23.000
This is a strategy of war, where there are no two winners or two losers.

03:23.500 --> 03:32.000
This is a strategy of a duel, when one person wins, and the other person loses.

03:33.000 --> 03:41.500
The advantage of this strategy is that the winner gets the maximum business result.

03:42.000 --> 03:45.500
All his goals are fulfilled and fulfilled 100%.

03:46.000 --> 03:49.500
He is the master of the position, he is the master of the conquered territory.

03:50.000 --> 03:53.500
However, the disadvantages are the same as in war.

03:54.000 --> 04:01.500
Most often we become the masters of the conquered territory, if we come to it as a conqueror.

04:02.000 --> 04:04.500
It is difficult to get some resources.

04:05.000 --> 04:09.500
Therefore, the strategy of the conqueror is not always successful.

04:10.000 --> 04:12.500
At the same time, it cannot be rejected.

04:13.000 --> 04:20.500
It is good in cases when you use it once and further relations do not make sense.

04:21.000 --> 04:23.500
Then it can be effective.

04:23.500 --> 04:30.000
If you see that during business negotiations your partner communicates,

04:30.500 --> 04:38.000
based on this strategy, you should accept it and be able to behave and interact with it.

04:38.500 --> 04:42.000
Although it is not always effective.

04:42.500 --> 04:46.000
The next strategy is the strategy of compromise.

04:46.500 --> 04:50.000
In these cases, the interaction is more constructive.

04:50.000 --> 04:52.500
Nobody burns the surface of the earth.

04:53.000 --> 04:55.500
However, everyone goes for a compromise.

04:56.000 --> 05:03.500
And the goals of both participants are not fulfilled 100%.

05:04.000 --> 05:10.500
The conditions of compromise are always softer and more natural than the strategy of the conqueror.

05:11.000 --> 05:16.500
You do not have to confront, you can discuss and do further business.

05:17.000 --> 05:19.500
You can cooperate for a long time and fruitfully.

05:20.000 --> 05:22.500
But the goals are not fulfilled.

05:23.000 --> 05:25.500
You always have to sacrifice something.

05:26.000 --> 05:27.500
It is not always convenient.

05:28.000 --> 05:35.500
Because in business it is very difficult to choose what to sacrifice and what to do.

05:36.000 --> 05:39.500
You always want to achieve the maximum result.

05:40.000 --> 05:45.500
Therefore, the strategy of compromise seems to be the most profitable and correct.

05:45.500 --> 05:50.000
We are inside the situation, we are immersed in it and do not see it from above.

05:50.500 --> 05:56.000
If we take the strategy of unity, the strategy called win-win,

05:56.500 --> 06:01.000
that is, to win and to win, this is the strategy of two participants who rise above the situation,

06:01.500 --> 06:09.000
who unite their business goals, who achieve 100% results in both cases.

06:09.000 --> 06:15.500
That is, the total percentage result is above all praises, it is 200% and more.

06:16.000 --> 06:17.500
Why does this happen?

06:18.000 --> 06:21.500
Of course, creativity, new ways of development, new ways of decision-making.

06:22.000 --> 06:27.500
It is very important to try to bring any negotiations to the strategy of unity.

06:28.000 --> 06:30.500
What are the disadvantages of the strategy of unity?

06:30.500 --> 06:41.000
They require a lot of resources to clarify points of view, to unite your opinions, to unite your positions.

06:41.500 --> 06:48.000
Therefore, effective communication skills are required in order to unite goals and find a common solution.

06:48.500 --> 06:57.000
Skills are needed to clarify positions, as well as to find a creative solution that would suit both sides.

06:57.000 --> 07:01.500
Today we will deal with all the elements of all three strategies.

07:02.000 --> 07:08.500
We will talk about what to do when the strategy of the conqueror is set against you.

07:09.000 --> 07:15.500
We will talk about how to effectively behave in the strategy of compromise, if it is imposed on you.

07:16.000 --> 07:24.500
And we will talk about how to effectively communicate and apply the strategy of unity, the strategy of win-win.

07:24.500 --> 07:26.000
The tactics of business communication.

07:26.500 --> 07:29.000
We have already talked about the strategies of business communication.

07:29.500 --> 07:40.000
This is a common approach to your business relations, both in negotiations, in everyday communication, and in public speech.

07:40.500 --> 07:43.000
Now we will talk about tactics.

07:43.500 --> 07:49.000
Tactics are specific tools for how to behave within your strategy.

07:49.000 --> 07:54.500
You don't need to think that every tactic is effective for a certain strategy.

07:55.000 --> 07:55.500
This is not the case.

07:56.000 --> 08:07.500
You can use any tactic in any strategy and correctly build a pattern of your communication that will lead you to your business result.

08:08.000 --> 08:11.500
Let's talk about specific tactics.

08:12.000 --> 08:14.500
You see that there are two columns on the slide.

08:15.000 --> 08:18.500
Indeed, one tactic is opposite to the other.

08:19.000 --> 08:24.500
For example, the first line is a closed tactic and the second line is an open tactic.

08:25.000 --> 08:27.500
What is it and how are they different?

08:28.000 --> 08:31.500
We see, we even say, here is a closed person and here is an open person.

08:32.000 --> 08:33.500
This is what it is.

08:34.000 --> 08:39.500
The other thing is that we psychologically refer to more closed and more open types.

08:40.000 --> 08:46.500
An effective communicator will specifically choose the right tactic, defined in this particular situation.

08:47.000 --> 08:48.500
The most successful and winning.

08:49.000 --> 08:54.500
When you use an open tactic, you are open-minded.

08:55.000 --> 08:59.500
You provide the maximum of the necessary information to the interlocutor.

09:00.000 --> 09:02.500
You answer all his questions.

09:03.000 --> 09:06.500
You are happy to clarify the circumstances.

09:07.000 --> 09:16.500
You reveal all the business and features of the specific situation that you are discussing.

09:17.500 --> 09:22.000
In a closed tactic, this is hidden.

09:22.500 --> 09:25.000
The maximum privacy of the information.

09:25.500 --> 09:27.000
We see only the minimum of information.

09:27.500 --> 09:29.000
The most public, the most open.

09:29.500 --> 09:33.000
Usually, it is provided in the form of documents, so as not to say unnecessary.

09:33.500 --> 09:35.000
You are minimally open to information.

09:35.500 --> 09:37.000
This is immediately noticeable to others.

09:37.500 --> 09:44.000
Therefore, this tactic is effective in the case when you feel an attack, feel pressure on you.

09:44.000 --> 09:52.500
Then a closed tactic will allow you to focus and stay inside your information field.

09:53.000 --> 09:57.500
An open tactic is effective in other cases and is considered more effective.

09:58.000 --> 10:03.500
Now it is said that an open tactic is the best way to motivate your subordinates.

10:04.000 --> 10:13.500
Many top managers say, why would I share my decisions, my forecasts and strategies with my subordinates.

10:14.000 --> 10:15.500
They should do what I say.

10:16.000 --> 10:20.500
It is important for them to hear what task they need to do.

10:21.000 --> 10:22.500
However, this is wrong.

10:23.000 --> 10:26.500
Because the low motivation of a simple, stupid execution is a slave.

10:27.000 --> 10:30.500
Now people are developed, they want to be personalities.

10:31.000 --> 10:34.500
They want to understand why they need to do a specific business task.

10:35.000 --> 10:41.500
Therefore, openness is sometimes the driving factor for successful motivation of employees.

10:41.500 --> 10:49.000
The next two tactics are role-based and personal.

10:49.500 --> 10:51.000
Why are they opposite?

10:51.500 --> 10:56.000
When a personal tactic is used, you are as open as possible.

10:56.500 --> 11:06.000
All your movements, all your thoughts, all your decisions come from your personality.

11:06.000 --> 11:11.500
Or as if from your personality, if you use it as a game.

11:12.000 --> 11:26.500
If you use a role-based tactic, then all decisions, words, everything you say comes from your business or social role.

11:27.000 --> 11:30.500
When is a personal tactic effective?

11:31.000 --> 11:34.500
In fact, in most cases of business communication in places.

11:34.500 --> 11:39.000
It is very successful for opening up your charisma in a public speech.

11:39.500 --> 11:42.000
It is not just a regular accountant.

11:42.500 --> 11:45.000
It is not an accountant standing in front of people, but a personality.

11:45.500 --> 11:49.000
It attracts attention, it causes trust.

11:49.500 --> 11:57.000
In conversations, in a comfortable emotional atmosphere, the most beneficial, the most effective is a personal tactic.

11:57.500 --> 12:01.000
Because you look like a personality, you look like a leader, an effective communicator.

12:02.000 --> 12:04.500
When is a role-based tactic used?

12:05.000 --> 12:07.500
A role-based tactic is used as a way of protection.

12:08.000 --> 12:14.500
Either from manipulation, or from too tough behavior of a partner or a negotiator.

12:15.000 --> 12:18.500
When you are pressured, you can close yourself and say,

12:19.000 --> 12:21.500
I'm just an accountant, I have to do what I do.

12:22.000 --> 12:23.500
It's a kind of shell, a kind of wall.

12:24.000 --> 12:26.500
Trust in you is undoubtedly falling.

12:27.000 --> 12:29.500
Your charisma, of course, is closing.

12:29.500 --> 12:31.000
But you are protecting yourself.

12:31.500 --> 12:37.000
The next two tactics are confrontation and partnership.

12:37.500 --> 12:40.000
What is the difference?

12:40.500 --> 12:48.000
Partnership causes immersion in the opinion of the interlocutor.

12:48.500 --> 12:52.000
You listen to him carefully, try to understand.

12:52.500 --> 12:55.000
You live his goals and thoughts.

12:55.500 --> 12:58.000
Emotionally support him.

12:58.000 --> 13:01.500
Try to unite your own and his interests.

13:02.000 --> 13:09.500
Confrontation is a tactic of stable behavior.

13:10.000 --> 13:13.500
You have set certain goals.

13:14.000 --> 13:16.500
You have found out what strategy goes to them.

13:17.000 --> 13:23.500
You do not show any flexibility, but are planned, move and move to your goal.

13:24.500 --> 13:31.000
All the suggested thoughts, opinions, arguments do not matter.

13:31.500 --> 13:33.000
You do what you think is necessary.

13:33.500 --> 13:36.000
You go and go in your own way.

13:36.500 --> 13:45.000
Again, confrontation is good, especially when you have chosen the winner's strategy.

13:45.500 --> 13:48.000
Of course, you go and go with a blunt wedge.

13:48.000 --> 13:55.500
But remember that a flexible person sitting opposite you can use new tools against this.

13:56.000 --> 13:57.500
Catch you in a trap.

13:58.000 --> 14:00.500
Chess players will say, make a fork.

14:01.000 --> 14:04.500
And then you will look funny.

14:05.000 --> 14:06.000
Be careful.

14:06.500 --> 14:09.500
Confrontation is a strong tactic.

14:10.000 --> 14:12.500
But it is too tough.

14:13.000 --> 14:14.500
Like a razor blade.

14:15.000 --> 14:17.500
It is sharp, but can easily break.

14:18.000 --> 14:22.500
When choosing a strategy, you should play a game.

14:23.000 --> 14:30.500
You should not choose this tactic and deny any flexibility.

14:31.000 --> 14:32.500
It can seriously interfere with you.

14:33.000 --> 14:36.500
I did not place these 6 tactics in two columns in vain.

14:37.000 --> 14:44.500
You noticed that the tactics of openness, personal tactics and partnership are located on the right.

14:44.500 --> 14:49.000
People smile and are successful and happy.

14:49.500 --> 14:51.000
On the left is a closed tactic.

14:51.500 --> 14:54.000
Role and confrontation.

14:54.500 --> 14:57.000
You are closed, you are ready for war.

14:57.500 --> 15:01.000
In fact, all these tactics are equally effective.

15:01.500 --> 15:03.000
You can use both.

15:03.500 --> 15:11.000
However, open personal tactics and partnership are considered more effective.

15:11.000 --> 15:16.500
You need to understand that you use them here and now.

15:17.000 --> 15:19.500
Because it is necessary at this particular moment.

15:20.000 --> 15:29.500
But the most effective negotiations, the most effective public speech is where personal and open tactics are used.

15:30.000 --> 15:38.500
Therefore, try to translate the tactics of your interlocutor and your tactics from the left column to the right.

15:38.500 --> 15:40.000
From confrontation to partnership.

15:40.500 --> 15:43.000
From role tactics to personal tactics.

15:43.500 --> 15:45.000
From closed to open.

15:45.500 --> 15:51.000
In fact, this information can be much more important than all the previous ones.

15:51.500 --> 15:58.000
Because the previous ones are often told in MBA courses, in business trainings.

15:58.500 --> 16:02.000
And they can be read in various books.

16:02.500 --> 16:06.000
What is written on this slide is very important.

16:06.000 --> 16:09.500
Because it has a great impact on business relations.

16:10.000 --> 16:11.500
But we often forget about it.

16:12.000 --> 16:15.500
What I will say now, you don't need to look for in others.

16:16.000 --> 16:17.500
Try to find it in yourself.

16:18.000 --> 16:22.500
Try to find ways to get away from this situation.

16:23.000 --> 16:26.500
And more effective and flexible behavior.

16:37.000 --> 16:38.500
Personal aspects of business relations.

16:39.000 --> 16:42.500
We will start with the fact that we will consider the institutions.

16:43.000 --> 16:46.500
The institutions of our personality, which on the one hand help us to live happily,

16:47.000 --> 16:52.500
help us to live calmly and not go crazy, but on the other hand, interfere with effective business communication.

16:54.000 --> 16:55.500
For example, let's take the first one.

16:56.000 --> 16:57.500
Estimation.

16:58.000 --> 16:59.500
What is it?

17:00.000 --> 17:01.500
And what is it bad about?

17:02.000 --> 17:03.500
And what is it good about?

17:03.500 --> 17:10.000
It is good because by evaluating people around us, we simplify our picture of the world.

17:10.500 --> 17:14.000
If we have evaluated this person, we know whether he is good or bad.

17:14.500 --> 17:17.000
We know what to expect from him, what to expect from his actions.

17:17.500 --> 17:20.000
And we can generalize some of his qualities.

17:20.500 --> 17:22.000
If it is bad in one, then bad in another.

17:22.500 --> 17:24.000
Everything becomes much easier.

17:24.500 --> 17:30.000
You don't have to spend every moment of time to understand what kind of person he is and what will happen next.

17:30.500 --> 17:32.000
On the other hand, it is very annoying.

17:32.000 --> 17:36.500
For example, if we see that this person is poorly dressed,

17:37.000 --> 17:40.500
we can decide that he has bad business qualities,

17:41.000 --> 17:44.500
that he is incompetent in the matter in which he came to deal with.

17:45.000 --> 17:49.500
Why? In fact, he may be just poorly dressed and very competent.

17:50.000 --> 17:51.500
There are many examples of this.

17:52.000 --> 17:56.500
Therefore, such an extrapolation of qualities, if he is bad in one, then bad in another,

17:57.000 --> 18:00.500
may interfere with us because we lose a lot of resources.

18:00.500 --> 18:04.000
For example, the resources of the person we will not have relations with later

18:04.500 --> 18:08.000
simply because he looks somehow illiterate.

18:08.500 --> 18:13.000
At the same time, if a person made a mistake once,

18:13.500 --> 18:17.000
that is, if he did something wrong at work,

18:17.500 --> 18:22.000
then our assessment system immediately decides that he will always do it wrong.

18:22.500 --> 18:27.000
It adjusts us to negative attitudes towards this person.

18:28.000 --> 18:31.500
Of course, I understand that even in personal relations this is often very important,

18:32.000 --> 18:34.500
but in business it is important twice as much.

18:35.000 --> 18:38.500
We stop supporting this person, we stop praising him.

18:39.000 --> 18:43.500
And it becomes even worse for him, he made a mistake.

18:44.000 --> 18:48.500
His self-esteem drops and he prefers to leave this workplace

18:49.000 --> 18:51.500
than to correct the mistake and move on.

18:52.500 --> 18:59.000
Therefore, the assessment system is good for us, but it is very distracting.

18:59.500 --> 19:05.000
It is best to decide every time what kind of person this person is,

19:05.500 --> 19:10.000
to explain everything very specifically, here and now,

19:10.500 --> 19:17.000
and to understand that we are talking only about those qualities that we are talking about,

19:17.000 --> 19:22.500
without letting our brain rest and relax, preventing us from perceiving others.

19:23.000 --> 19:26.500
The next setting is the rigidity setting.

19:27.000 --> 19:30.500
Young people who communicate with their parents are familiar with it.

19:31.000 --> 19:34.500
This setting is also called the problem of fathers and children.

19:35.000 --> 19:40.500
Rigidity is the inability to perceive new things in the psyche.

19:41.000 --> 19:43.500
The inability to change very quickly.

19:43.500 --> 19:48.000
The inability to change their opinion due to some arguments.

19:48.500 --> 19:53.000
Most often we say, yes, I hear this setting perfectly and I know it perfectly.

19:53.500 --> 19:58.000
Everyone around me is so rigid, I tell them something, but they don't hear me.

19:58.500 --> 20:02.000
But in fact, maybe they don't even need to be told this.

20:02.500 --> 20:06.000
Maybe it's worth listening to what they say and taking their point of view.

20:06.500 --> 20:09.000
In business, it is especially important to be flexible.

20:09.500 --> 20:13.000
If you move on a break, you can always move in one direction and lose the market.

20:13.500 --> 20:17.000
Therefore, the rigidity setting simplifies our life.

20:17.500 --> 20:21.000
Because the world is as it is, and you don't need to spend extra resources

20:21.500 --> 20:25.000
to understand something new, to understand new interactions in this world.

20:25.500 --> 20:28.000
But in fact, any successful businessman will say,

20:28.500 --> 20:33.000
if you don't absorb new things, don't find new ways of development,

20:33.500 --> 20:38.000
don't accept the creativity of others and the creativity of your own group,

20:38.500 --> 20:42.000
then it is impossible to win in the market, it is impossible to become a leader.

20:42.000 --> 20:47.500
Therefore, the rigidity setting is natural for the elderly.

20:48.000 --> 20:51.500
With age, rigidity is normally enhanced.

20:52.000 --> 20:55.500
But nevertheless, listen to yourself.

20:56.000 --> 21:00.500
Maybe you have already become completely confident in one opinion.

21:01.000 --> 21:03.500
Then it is worth changing it, it is worth getting used to it.

21:04.000 --> 21:06.500
Around the universe of opinions, the universe of choices,

21:07.000 --> 21:09.500
you can find new ways of development.

21:09.500 --> 21:13.000
This will help you to solve the strategy of win-win.

21:13.500 --> 21:17.000
The next setting is the ego-centrism setting.

21:17.500 --> 21:20.000
This is a very interesting setting.

21:20.500 --> 21:24.000
We are talking about an egoist, an egocentric person

21:24.500 --> 21:28.000
who is constantly looking for attention, constantly in the center of attention,

21:28.500 --> 21:32.000
constantly attracting others to himself, who is always thinking about himself,

21:32.500 --> 21:36.000
whose self-confidence is very high.

21:36.500 --> 21:39.000
In fact, this is not so.

21:39.500 --> 21:45.000
The ego-centrism setting, on the contrary, prevents us from gaining self-confidence,

21:45.500 --> 21:48.000
prevents us from attracting others.

21:48.500 --> 21:51.000
Why does this happen?

21:51.500 --> 21:58.000
The ego-centrism setting itself says that everything that happens around a person

21:58.500 --> 22:02.000
is taken into account.

22:02.500 --> 22:07.000
Everything that happens, happens either for good or for evil.

22:07.000 --> 22:13.500
All the people who are around him are for the sake of this person.

22:14.000 --> 22:15.500
But this is certainly not so.

22:16.000 --> 22:19.500
After all, when they laugh behind our backs, they do not always laugh at us.

22:20.000 --> 22:22.500
But we often think that this is so.

22:23.000 --> 22:26.500
Therefore, when the ego-centrism setting presses very hard on you,

22:27.000 --> 22:31.500
you are always worried about who and what and how thought about you.

22:32.000 --> 22:35.500
You always think that if some kind of failure has happened,

22:35.500 --> 22:39.000
then it is directed against you by evil.

22:39.500 --> 22:43.000
You always think that if you are not noticed,

22:43.500 --> 22:46.000
then these people are angry with you.

22:46.500 --> 22:48.000
They direct their aggression at you.

22:48.500 --> 22:50.000
But this is not so.

22:50.500 --> 22:53.000
These people are just people, and they have their own world, their own universe.

22:53.500 --> 22:56.000
You have your own world, and you have your own universe.

22:56.500 --> 22:58.000
They do not necessarily intersect.

22:58.500 --> 23:01.000
In the same way, in order to attract the attention of others,

23:01.500 --> 23:05.000
you need to get away from this setting.

23:05.500 --> 23:09.000
An boring lecturer who reads his lecture in a dull voice,

23:09.500 --> 23:15.000
